  "doc_id": "26567",
  "text": "Methylene blue dye adsorption on SW is greatly influenced by the initial pH of the solution. Process pH greatly affects the surface binding sites of biomaterials and the ionization process of dye molecules. In order to optimize the pH, adsorption of the dye over SW was carried out in the pH range 2 to 8. From Fig. 3 , when the pH increases from 2 to 4 there is a steep increase in adsorption of methylene blue and no significant change in the amount adsorbed by further increase of pH up to 8. Similar findings were reported by many authors so far [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . The pH trend observed clearly indicates that the maximum adsorption of methylene blue takes place at both neutral and slightly basic pH. This can be explained by the electrostatic interaction of methylene blue (because of its cationic structure) with negatively charged surface of the SW. The protonation of MB takes place in a highly acidic medium, while on the other hand, with decrease in acidity of the solution the dye becomes deprotonated. Another possibility can be the development of positive charge on the adsorbent in highly acidic solution, which inhibits the adsorption of dye, resulting in low adsorption. However, on increasing the basicity, the uptake of the dye increases due to a change in its polarity.",
